This dashlet lists the tasks assigned to you, including invitations to join sites. You can filter the list to view different types of tasks.

From here you can:

  • Edit a task to manage it
  • View a single task
  • Open the My Tasks page to manage all of your tasks
  • Start a process to create tasks for others or yourself

Enter the words you read below
This a short tour of the Process Editor. The next few steps will guide you through the different sections of the application to get you started. Press the ESC key to stop at any time..
All the available constructs to create a business process can be found here. They are arranged in logical groups. To open a group simply click on it
This is the work space on which you create your business process. Drag elements from the palette on the left and drop them on this canvas to start modeling.
Here is an example how you get started with modeling
Here you can configure the properties of a business process construct. Simply select the item on the canvas and its properties will be shown. Click on the property if you want to edit it
All the actions can be found here: saving or validating a model, copy and pasting parts of a process, and so on. Hover over the buttons to get a description for an action.
That's it! You can now start modeling your processes. If you have any questions, feel free to ask them on the Alfresco BPM Forum

When you are connecting process steps with each other using sequence flow (those arrows between process steps), you might find that these sequence flows cross each other or you would like to arrange them differently. To do this, you can add or remove a bend point to or from a sequence flow.

As shown below in the picture, you first click the 'add bendpoint' and then click on a sequence flow to add it. Note that the sequence flow will show you a subtle indication in green to show the bendpoint can be added there.

Removing a bendpoint again follows a similar pattern: click the 'Remove bendpoint' button and click on the bend point to remove it again.

The endpoint configuration (each cluster has only one) needs to point to a REST installation. This endpoint retrieves and manages the data used in the other sections (for example deployments, process definitions, and so on) of this application.

This section allows you to define a 'master configuration' for the cluster. All instances in the cluster will use this configuration when they boot up (if the cluster config jar is on the classpath or if the corresponding properties are set). If not set, the instances will use their local configuration files.

It is important that all members of the same cluster use the same settings.

To facilitate this, a Java Archive jar (jar) can be downloaded by following the link below. This jar contains the configuration needed for a Process Services instance to communicate with the Process Services Admin Application.The jar simply needs to be put on the classpath and will be automatically used.
The following field is the base URL which will be used to send information back to this Admin Application. Change it if, for some reason, the URL does not match the URL used to view this web UI.
Leave blank to keep current password

When a cluster configuration is deleted, note that you also should remove the configuration jar (or properties file) for this cluster configuration from the classpath of the nodes.
Cannot delete this cluster configuration: there needs to be one cluster configuration at minimum and this is the only cluster configuration defined in the system.
Each cluster needs to have a unique name. Each of the engine instances will need to provide this cluster name to join the cluster.

Each cluster needs to have a user name and password. Each of the Process Services engine instances that want to interchange data with the Process Services Admin Application will need to provide these credentials in their communication.
When you enable master configuration, process instances that are members of this cluster boot up using the master configuration.

Each Process Services instance which is a member of this cluster will send metrics (for example JVM and usage metrics) back to the Process Services Admin App. The following setting defines how frequent these metrics are gathered and sent.

Fill this in (ignoring the settings above) if the datasource is configured in an application server and exposed through Jndi.

It is advisable to leave this set to 'false', and upgrade the database schema using the SQL scripts. If set to 'true' the first node in the cluster to boot up will auto-upgrade the schema. This could cause issues when multiple nodes boot up at the same time since data definition is often not transactional.

Each Process Services engine instance has a job executor component, which is responsible for executing background tasks such as timers and async continuations of business processes. It is advisable, however, to only have a small number (one, two or more for very high load scenarios) of jobexecutors activated. The value of this setting will be used to activate or deactivate job executors as necessary in the cluster.

The maximum number of (parsed) process definitions that is kept in memory. Parsing a process definition is resource-intensive, so it is advisable to have a large enough cache while not using too much memory (default: unlimited).
The number of database IDÍs that a Process Services engine reserves for use when creating new entities (default: 100). When all IDÍs have been used, a new block is reserved in the database.
The job executor is the component responsible for, amongst other things, executing timers and asynchronous continuations (referred to as 'jobs') of business processes.

The job executor works in two phases: first, jobs are 'acquired' by locking jobs for a certain amount of time (to avoid conflicts between multiple job executors). In the second phase, the acquired jobs are executed by (typically) a separate threadpool. This value determines how many job are acquired per query for phase 1. When more than one job executor is active in a cluster, it is advised to set this value to 1 to avoid deadlocks. Default value is 1.
The time (in ms) that is waited after all jobs have been executed or no jobs have been found. This is to avoid hitting the database way too much. Default value is 10000 ms.

The time (in ms) that a job is locked by one job executor component. When the time is passed, but the job is not yet executed, the job can again be acquired by other job executor. This is to avoid that one failing job executor would halt job execution forever. Default value is 5 minutes (300000 ms)
The minimum amount of threads in the thread pool that are kept active for executing jobs. Only applicable for the default job executor.

The default job executor first acquires jobs and puts them on queue before executing them in a thread pool. This value determines how many jobs are kept on this queue. Only applicable for the default job executor (does not apply for Spring job executor for example or custom implementations).
The maximum amount of threads in the thread pool that are created for executing jobs. Only applicable for the default job executor.

Allows configuration of the connection pool of the datasource created by Alfresco Process Services. These settings are only applicable if Alfresco Process Services is responsible for creating the datasource (as opposed to jndi, for example) and has not received any Spring injections.
The maximum time a connection can be used before it 'may' be given away again.
The time to wait before retrying to get a connection.
This is only needed when using the email functionality in your business processes.
Fill this in (ignoring the settings above) if the mailserver is configured in an application server and exposed through Jndi.
